<br>
You put a lot of work into analyzing the forumlas involved. Thanks for all the effort: it helps to improve the estimation. I'll address the issues you raise, but skimp a bit on the forumlas to keep it readable. For more information on the derivation of my forumlas, visit the following thread: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showMessage?topicID=603.topic">pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffe...=603.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
On to your comments:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Specialization effects.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yeah, I negelected to account for these. When I originally derived the formula, AA skills weren't in yet, and the exact effect of specialization was not known (by me, at least). We now have a better understanding of both, and future versions will account for it. Interestingly enough, the numbers worked out close enough when I discounted specialization altogether (meaning predicted results were close to measured results).<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Med tick missing chance based off casting time of spell (ie, on combat medding). Looks like the chance is 50% in your table?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes. This is a heuristic and is lower than you would expect because of sit agro. I found I was unable to med in combat as much as I liked because sit agro would prevent it. I discounted meditation in combat entirely when item nuking because I found that when I was item nuking I was never meditating in combat, ever. I was either clicking or casting or standing to avoid sit agro.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The &quot;minutes&quot; are in &quot;minutes per hour engaged&quot; right?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Your item calculations are a bit wonkey.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes, this is a bit convoluted. Basically, using straightline theoretical numbers always came out significantly higher than my measured numbers. I struggled with a few approaches to make everything balance out and hit on the right factor when I accounted for average fight time and item cast time. The above thread covers this in more detail, but think about the PoG robe for a minute. It has a cast time of 28 seconds. Lets say that your average fight time is 30 seconds. Some fights will be more, some less. If you are only item nuking, and click your robe as soon as the pull arrives at the camp, your nuke will land on a corpse an average of every other fight (some fights will take less than 30 seconds, remember). If you are responsible for snare, then the mob will likely be in runaway mode before your nuke lands, so it will move out of range before the nuke goes off every single time (not to mention that you'd find yourself fired from snare duty if you kept that up). The formula I concocted is based on (1/(1+x)) and gives the shape I liked, approaching zero when combat time = click time, but approaching full right click efficiency when combat time approaches infinity. The actual formula is as follows:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ACT = Average Combat Time (per opponent, in seconds)<br>
IAT = Item Activation Time (in seconds: raw number + 1)<br>
IDPS = Item's effective DPS<br>
SE = Item's Spell Efficiency. I use 100% for lure, 95% for magic, and 90% for fire/cold.<br>
X = Item use factor (roughly, how many times in a combat the item could theorhetically be used).<br>
<br>
Here are the formulas:<br>
X = ACT / IAT<br>
rawdps = (item dmg) / IAT<br>
IDPS = SE * rawdps * (1 - (2/(X + 1)))<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Applying this forumla to my Rend Robe sessions predicted damage within about 5%. Straight line formulas (such as yours) usually overestimated damage from items by 30-50%.<br>
<br>
I should note that I completely discounted cast time of wizard nukes because I found that agro prevented me from nuking/medding efficiently enough for it to become a factor.<br>
<br>
Anyway, thanks again for taking the time to carefully examine my formulas and provide some insightful commentary. I will account for specialization (and Spec Mastery) in my next version, but there's no ETA on this being done. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/12/02 5:55:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=641.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> mathie</span><hr size=1> I can see how &quot;no chance to use item&quot; would occur reasonably often.  Interesting heuristic for it.  =)  If item_time is reasonably larger (like a factor of 2 or so) than combat_time, I think you get (combat_time/item_time - 1/2) item-nukes off.  (I did some similar analysis over in DaoC, and it worked out well -- the combat will end uniformly within a delay cycle, so half the time you lose a nuke).  <br>
